WRITING.TEXT:
These underlying numbers also represent the coefficients for many Maclaurin or Taylor Series, which are ways to approximate any mathematic function using a polynomial.
For many Maclaurin series, these coefficients are the inverse of the factorial of the exponent, so for a squared term, it would be 1/2, for a cubed term, it would be 1/6, for a quartic term, 1/24. The reason these are what they are is when you take the derivative of that polynomial as many times as the exponent specifies, the coefficient is always 1 when there is no polynomial left to coincide.
For example, the derivative of 1/2 x^2 is 1x, whose derivative is 1.
The derivative of 1/6 x^3 is 1/2 x^2, whose derivative is 1x, whose derivative is 1.
The derivative of 1/24 x^4 is 1/6 x^3, and so on.
Using this, I can guarantee you that the next increment level for your series will be 120, and after that 720, and then after that 5040, which are accordingly the factoriala of 5,6, and 7.
